# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ini-format
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Early character encodings that originated with optical or electrical telegraphy and in early computers could only represent a subset of the characters used in languages, sometimes restricted to upper case letters, numerals and limited punctuation.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Over time, encodings capable of representing more characters were created, such as ASCII, ISO/IEC 8859, and Unicode encodings such as UTF-8 and UTF-16.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] The most popular character encoding on the World Wide Web is UTF-8, which is used in 98.9% of surveyed web sites, as of January 2026.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] In application programs and operating system tasks, both UTF-8 and UTF-16 are popular options.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] The history of character codes illustrates the evolving need for machine-mediated character-based symbolic information over a distance, using once-novel electrical means.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] The earliest codes were based upon manual and hand-written encoding and cyphering systems, such as Bacon's cipher, Braille, international maritime signal flags, and the 4-digit encoding of Chinese characters for a Chinese telegraph code (Hans Schjellerup, 1869).
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] With the adoption of electrical and electro-mechanical techniques these earliest codes were adapted to the new capabilities and limitations of the early machines.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] The earliest well-known electrically transmitted character code, Morse code, introduced in the 1840s, used a system of four "symbols" (short signal, long signal, short space, long space) to generate codes of variable length.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Though some commercial use of Morse code was via machinery, it was often used as a manual code, generated by hand on a telegraph key and decipherable by ear, and persists in amateur radio and aeronautical use.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Most codes are of fixed per-character length or variable-length sequences of fixed-length codes (e.g.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Common examples of character encoding systems include Morse code, the Baudot code, the American Standard Code for Information Interchange (ASCII) and Unicode.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Unicode, a well-defined and extensible encoding system, has replaced most earlier character encodings, but the path of code development to the present is fairly well known.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] The Baudot code, a five-bit encoding, was created by Émile Baudot in 1870, patented in 1874, modified by Donald Murray in 1901, and standardized by CCITT as International Telegraph Alphabet No.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] The name *baudot* has been erroneously applied to ITA2 and its many variants.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] ITA2 suffered from many shortcomings and was often improved by many equipment manufacturers, sometimes creating compatibility issues.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Herman Hollerith invented punch card data encoding in the late 19th century to analyze census data.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Initially, each hole position represented a different data element, but later, numeric information was encoded by numbering the lower rows 0 to 9, with a punch in a column representing its row number.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Later alphabetic data was encoded by allowing more than one punch per column.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Electromechanical tabulating machines represented date internally by the timing of pulses relative to the motion of the cards through the machine.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] When IBM went to electronic processing, starting with the IBM 603 Electronic Multiplier, it used a variety of binary encoding schemes that were tied to the punch card code.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] IBM used several binary-coded decimal (BCD) six-bit character encoding schemes, starting as early as 1953 in its 702 and 704 computers, and in its later 7000 Series and 1400 series, as well as in associated peripherals.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Since the punched card code then in use was limited to digits, upper-case English letters and a few special characters, six bits were sufficient.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] These BCD encodings extended existing simple four-bit numeric encoding to include alphabetic and special characters, mapping them easily to punch-card encoding which was already in widespread use.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] IBM's codes were used primarily with IBM equipment.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Other computer vendors of the era had their own character codes, often six-bit, such as the encoding used by the UNIVAC I.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] They usually had the ability to read tapes produced on IBM equipment.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] IBM's BCD encodings were the precursors of their Extended Binary-Coded Decimal Interchange Code (usually abbreviated as EBCDIC), an eight-bit encoding scheme developed in 1963 for the IBM System/360 that featured a larger character set, including lower case letters.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] In 1959, the U.S. military defined its Fieldata code, a six-or seven-bit code, introduced by the U.S.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] While Fieldata addressed many of the then-modern issues (e.g. letter and digit codes arranged for machine collation), it fell short of its goals and was short-lived.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] In 1963 the first ASCII code was released (X3.4-1963) by the ASCII committee (which contained at least one member of the Fieldata committee, W.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Leubbert), which addressed most of the shortcomings of Fieldata, using a simpler seven-bit code.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Many of the changes were subtle, such as collatable character sets within certain numeric ranges.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] ASCII63 was a success, widely adopted by industry, and with the follow-up issue of the 1967 ASCII code (which added lower-case letters and fixed some "control code" issues) ASCII67 was adopted fairly widely.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] ASCII67's American-centric nature was somewhat addressed in the European ECMA-6 standard.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Eight-bit extended ASCII encodings, such as various vendor extensions and the ISO/IEC 8859 series, supported all ASCII characters as well as additional non-ASCII characters.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] In 1985, the average personal computer user's hard disk drive could store only about 10 megabytes, and it cost approximately US$250 on the wholesale market (and much higher if purchased separately at retail), so it was very important at the time to make every bit count.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] The compromise solution that was eventually found and developed into Unicode was to break the assumption (dating back to telegraph codes) that each character should always directly correspond to a particular sequence of bits.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Instead, characters would first be mapped to a universal intermediate representation in the form of abstract numbers called code points.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Code points would then be represented in a variety of ways and with various default numbers of bits per character (code units) depending on context.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] To encode code points higher than the length of the code unit, such as above 256 for eight-bit units, the solution was to implement variable-length encodings where an escape sequence would signal that subsequent bits should be parsed as a higher code point.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] The various terms related to character encoding are often used inconsistently or incorrectly.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Historically, the same standard would specify a repertoire of characters and how they were to be encoded into a stream of code units – usually with a single character per code unit.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] However, due to the emergence of more sophisticated character encodings, the distinction between terms has become important.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] A character is the smallest unit of text that has semantic value.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] In linguistics, this is called a grapheme and each of the various ways it may be written are called glyphs.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] What constitutes a character varies between character encodings.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] For example, for letters with diacritics, there are two distinct approaches that can be taken to encode them.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] They can be encoded either as a single unified character (known as a precomposed character), or as separate characters that combine into a single glyph.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] The former simplifies the text handling system, but the latter allows any letter/diacritic combination to be used in text.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Some writing systems, such as Arabic and Hebrew, have graphemes whose shape and joining depend on context.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] A character set is a collection of characters used to represent text.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] For example, the Latin alphabet and Greek alphabet are character sets.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] A coded character set is a character set with each item uniquely mapped to a numberic value.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] This is also known as a code page, although that term is generally antiquated.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Originally, *code page* referred to a page number in an IBM manual that defined a particular character encoding.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Other vendors, including Microsoft, SAP, and Oracle Corporation, also published their own code pages, including notable Windows code page and code page 437.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Despite no longer referring to specific pages in a manual, many character encodings are still identified to by the same number.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Likewise, the term *code page* is still used to refer to character encoding.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] In Unix and Unix-like systems, the term *charmap* is commonly used; usually in the larger context of locales.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] IBM's Character Data Representation Architecture (CDRA) designates each entity with a coded character set identifier (CCSID), which is variously called a *charset*, *character set*, *code page*, or *CHARMAP*.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] A character repertoire is a set of characters that can be represented by a particular coded character set.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] The repertoire may be closed, meaning that no additions are allowed without creating a new standard (as is the case with ASCII and most of the ISO-8859 series); or it may be open, allowing additions (as is the case with Unicode and to a limited extent Windows code pages).
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] A code point is the value or position of a character in a coded character set.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] A code point is represented by a sequence of code units.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Code space is the range of numerical values spanned by a coded character set.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] A code unit is the minimum bit combination that can represent a character in a character encoding (in computer science terms, it is the word size of the character encoding).
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Common code units include 7-bit, 8-bit, 16-bit, and 32-bit.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] In some encodings, some characters are encoded as multiple code units.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Unicode and its parallel standard, the ISO/IEC 10646 Universal Character Set, together constitute a unified standard for character encoding.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] The purpose of this decomposition is to establish a universal set of characters that can be encoded in a variety of ways.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] To describe the model precisely, Unicode uses existing terms and defines new terms.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] An abstract character repertoire (ACR) is the full set of abstract characters that a system supports.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Unicode has an open repertoire, meaning that new characters will be added to the repertoire over time.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] A coded character set (CCS) is a function that maps characters to *code points* (each code point represents one character).
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] For example, in a given repertoire, the capital letter "A" in the Latin alphabet might be represented by the code point 65, the character "B" by 66, and so on.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Multiple coded character sets may share the same character repertoire; for example ISO/IEC 8859-1 and IBM code pages 037 and 500 all cover the same repertoire but map them to different code points.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Hardware and software systems typically have a maximum "native" word length, such as 16 or 32 bits.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] A character encoding may define code points whose length exceeds a system's native word length.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] *A character encoding form* (CEF) is the mapping of code points to *code units* that break up a code point in a standardized way so that each code unit fits within the system's word length.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] For example, a computer that represents numbers in 16-bit units can only represent code points up to 65,535 per unit, but larger code points can be represented using multiple 16-bit units as defined by the CEF.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] A character encoding scheme (CES) is the mapping of code units to a sequence of octets to facilitate storage on an octet-based file system or transmission over an octet-based network.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] See comparison of Unicode encodings for a detailed discussion.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] There may be a higher-level protocol which supplies additional information to select the particular variant of a Unicode character, particularly where there are regional variants that have been 'unified' in Unicode as the same character.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] An example is the XML attribute xml:lang.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] The Unicode model uses the term "character map" for other systems which directly assign a sequence of characters to a sequence of bytes, covering all of the CCS, CEF and CES layers.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] A character is commonly documented as 'U+' followed by its code point value in hexadecimal.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] The range of valid code points (the code space) for the Unicode standard is U+0000 to U+10FFFF, inclusive, divided in 17 planes, identified by the numbers 0 to 16.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Characters in the range U+0000 to U+FFFF are in plane 0, called the Basic Multilingual Plane (BMP).
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] This plane contains the most commonly used characters.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Characters in the range U+10000 to U+10FFFF in the other planes are called supplementary characters.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Consider, "ab̲c𐐀" – a string containing a Unicode combining character (U+0332 ◌̲ COMBINING LOW LINE to underline the ⟨b⟩) as well as a supplementary character (U+10400 𐐀 DESERET CAPITAL LETTER LONG I).
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Note in particular that 𐐀 is represented with either one 32-bit value (UTF-32), two 16-bit values (UTF-16), or four 8-bit values (UTF-8).
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] Although each of those forms uses the same total number of bits (32) to represent the grapheme, it is not obvious how the actual numeric byte values are related.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] To support environments using multiple character encodings, software has been developed to translate text between character encoding schemes, a process known as transcoding.
[src:ini-format/character-encoding] The most used character encoding on the web is UTF-8, used in 98.9% of surveyed web sites, as of January 2026.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] A **configuration file**, also known as **config file**, is a file that stores data used to configure a software system such as an application, a server or an operating system.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Some applications provide a tool to create, modify, and verify the syntax of their configuration files – sometimes via graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] For context, system administrators may be expected to create and modify text config files via a text editor.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] For server processes and operating-system settings, there is often no standard tool, but operating systems may provide graphical interfaces such as YaST or debconf.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Some computer programs only read their configuration files at startup.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Others periodically check the configuration files for changes.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Users can instruct some programs to re-read the configuration files and apply the changes to the current process, or indeed to read arbitrary files as a configuration file.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] There are no definitive standards or strong conventions.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] In general, a config file can have any format.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] The format that applies to a particular system is determined by the design of that system.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Often, a standardized format is used since it allows for using tools designed for the format even if not designed for the consuming system.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] In particular, general-purpose serialization formats, such as JSON, XML, and YAML, are often used in open-source and platform-neutral software.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] The specifications for these formats are generally publicly available to support wide-spread use.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] The following table compares notable formats used for configuration data.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] The *syntax typing* column indicates whether the syntax supports data types.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] A format has syntax-typing if a value's type is specified by syntax – e.g.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] `true` is a Boolean while `"true"` is a string.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] A format does not have syntax-typing if a value's type is based on semantics – e.g.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] `true` and `"true"` are both Boolean if the parser expects a Boolean.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Opinions on the value of syntax-typing vary.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] The following are examples of config files organized by the operating systems on which they are commonly used.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Many different file formats are used on Unix and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Even so, there is a strong tradition of using human-editable, plain text formats including simple key–value pair.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Filename extensions of `.cnf`, `.conf`, `.cfg`, `.cf` or `.ini` are often used.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Many formats allow comments, in which case, individual settings can be disabled by prepending with the comment character.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Often the default configuration files contain extensive internal documentation in the form of comments and man files are also typically used to document the format and options available.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] System-wide software often uses configuration files stored in `/etc`, while user applications often use a "dotfile" – a file or directory in the home directory prefixed with a period, which in Unix hides the file or directory from casual listing.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Since this causes pollution, newer user applications generally make their own folder in the `.config` directory, a standardized subdirectory of the home directory.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Similar to config files, a run command (rc) shell script can configure a shell session.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Often, such scripts are named with an `rc` suffix after the consuming program's name such as `.xinitrc`, `.vimrc`, `.bashrc`, `xsane.rc`.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] By contrast, IBM's AIX uses an Object Data Manager (ODM) database to store much of its system settings.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] MS-DOS primarily relied on the `CONFIG.SYS` config file, a plain text file with simple key–value pairs (e.g.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] MS-DOS 6 introduced the INI-file format.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Similar to an rc file, the batch file named `AUTOEXEC.BAT` ran commands on startup.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Both these files were retained up to Windows 98SE, which still ran on top of MS-DOS.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] DOS applications used a wide variety of individual configuration files, most of them binary, proprietary and undocumented - and there were no common conventions or formats.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Early Windows operating systems heavily utilized plain-text INI files which served as the primary mechanism to configure the operating system and applications.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] The APIs to read and write from these still exist in Windows, but after 1993, Microsoft began to steer developers away from using INI files and toward storing settings in the registry, a hierarchical database to store configuration settings, which was introduced with Windows NT.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Later systems use XML and other formats instead of the registry.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] The Property List is the standard configuration file format in macOS (as well as in iOS, NeXTSTEP, GNUstep and Cocoa applications).
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] It uses the filename extension `.plist`.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] IBM's OS/2 uses a binary format, also with a .INI suffix, but this differs from the Windows versions.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] It contains a list of lists of untyped key–value pairs.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Two files control system-wide settings: OS2.INI and OS2SYS.INI.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] Application developers can choose whether to use them or to create a specific file for their applications.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] HarmonyOS and OpenHarmony-based operating systems use JSON config files, named `config.json`.
[src:ini-format/configuration-file] The platform IDE, DevEco Studio, provides methods for editing `config.json`.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] An **environment variable** is a user-definable value that can affect the way running processes will behave on a computer.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] Environment variables are part of the environment in which a process runs.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] For example, a running process can query the value of the TEMP environment variable to discover a suitable location to store temporary files, or the HOME or USERPROFILE variable to find the directory structure owned by the user running the process.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] They were introduced in their modern form in 1979 with Version 7 Unix, so are included in all Unix operating system flavors and variants from that point onward including Linux and macOS.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] From PC DOS 2.0 in 1982, all succeeding Microsoft operating systems, including Microsoft Windows, and OS/2 also have included them as a feature, although with somewhat different syntax, usage and standard variable names.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] In all Unix and Unix-like systems, as well as on Windows, each process has its own separate set of environment variables.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] By default, when a process is created, it inherits a duplicate run-time environment of its parent process, except for explicit changes made by the parent when it creates the child.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] At the API level, these changes must be done between running `fork` and `exec`.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] Alternatively, from command shells such as bash, a user can change environment variables for a particular command invocation by indirectly invoking it via `env` or using the `ENVIRONMENT_VARIABLE=VALUE <command>` notation.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] A running program can access the values of environment variables for configuration purposes.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] Shell scripts and batch files use environment variables to communicate data and preferences to child processes.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] They can also be used to store temporary values for reference later in a shell script.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] However, in Unix, non-exported variables are preferred for this as they do not leak outside the process.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] In Unix, an environment variable that is changed in a script or compiled program will only affect that process and possibly child processes.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] The parent process and any unrelated processes will not be affected.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] Similarly, changing or removing a variable's value inside a DOS or Windows batch file will change the variable for the duration of `COMMAND.COM`or `CMD.EXE`'s existence, respectively.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] In Unix, the environment variables are normally initialized during system startup by the system init startup scripts, and hence inherited by all other processes in the system.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] Users can, and often do, augment them in the profile script for the command shell they are using.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] In Microsoft Windows, each environment variable's default value is stored in the Windows Registry or set in the `AUTOEXEC.BAT` file.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] On Unix, a setuid program is given an environment chosen by its caller, but it runs with different authority from its caller.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] The dynamic linker will usually load code from locations specified by the environment variables `$LD_LIBRARY_PATH` and `$LD_PRELOAD` and run it with the process's authority.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] If a setuid program did this, it would be insecure, because its caller could get it to run arbitrary code and hence misuse its authority.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] For this reason, libc unsets these environment variables at startup in a setuid process. setuid programs usually unset unknown environment variables and check others or set them to reasonable values.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] In general, the collection of environment variables function as an associative array where both the keys and values are strings.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] The interpretation of characters in either string differs among systems.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] When data structures such as lists need to be represented, it is common to use a colon (common on Unix and Unix-like) or semicolon-delineated (common on Windows and DOS) list.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] The variables can be used both in scripts and on the command line.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] They are usually referenced by putting special symbols in front of or around the variable name.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] By convention, names of environment variables are normally expressed in all capital letters.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] This helps keep environment variables distinctly different from other variables and identifiers used in programming codes.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] Nevertheless, note that case sensitivity in environment variable names differs between operating systems.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] That is, Unix-like operating systems are case-sensitive with respect to environment variable names, while DOS, OS/2, and Windows are not case-sensitive.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] In most Unix and Unix-like command-line shells, an environment variable's value is retrieved by placing a `$` sign before the variable's name.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] If necessary, the name can also be surrounded by braces.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] In Unix and Unix-like systems, the names of environment variables are case-sensitive.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] The command **`env`** displays all environment variables and their values.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] The command **`printenv`** can also be used to print a single variable by giving that variable name as the sole argument to the command.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows command-line interpreters such as `COMMAND.COM` and `CMD.EXE`, an environment variable is retrieved by placing a `%` sign before and after it.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows command-line interpreters as well as their API, upper or lower case is not distinguished for environment variable names.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] The environment variable named `HOMEDRIVE` contains the drive letter (plus its trailing `:` colon) of the user's home directory, whilst `HOMEPATH` contains the full path of the user's home directory within that drive.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] The command **`SET`** (with no arguments) displays all environment variables and their values.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] In Windows NT and later `set` can also be used to print all variables whose name begins with a given prefix by giving the prefix as the sole argument to the command.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] In PowerShell, upper or lower case is not distinguished for environment variable names.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] The commands `env` and `set` can be used to set environment variables and are often incorporated directly into the shell.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] The following commands can also be used, but are often dependent on a certain shell.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] A few simple principles govern how environment variables achieve their effect.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] Environment variables are local to the process in which they were set.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] If two shell processes are spawned and the value of an environment variable is changed in one, that change will not be seen by the other.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] When a child process is created, it inherits all the environment variables and their values from the parent process.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] Usually, when a program calls another program, it first creates a child process by forking, then the child adjusts the environment as needed and lastly the child replaces itself with the program to be called.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] This procedure gives the calling program control over the environment of the called program.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] In Unix shells, variables may be assigned without the **`export`** keyword.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] Variables defined in this way are displayed by the **`set`** command, but are *not* true environment variables, as they are stored only by the shell and are unknown to all other processes.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] The `printenv` command will not display them, and child processes do not inherit them.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] The persistence of an environment variable can be session-wide or system-wide.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] The **`SET`** command without any arguments displays all environment variables along with their values; **`SET " "`**, zero or more spaces, will include internal variables too.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] In `CMD.EXE`, it is possible to assign local variables that will not be global using the **`SETLOCAL`** command and **`ENDLOCAL`** to restore the environment.
[src:ini-format/environment-variable-p01] In PHP the `putenv()` function should be used.
