[src:ini-format/ini-file] An **INI file** is a configuration file for computer software that consists of plain text with a structure and syntax comprising key–value pairs organized in sections.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] The name of these configuration files comes from the filename extension *INI*, short for initialization, used in the MS-DOS operating system, which popularized this method of software configuration.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] The format has become an informal standard in many contexts of configuration, but many applications on other operating systems use different filename extensions, such as *conf* and *cfg*.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] The primary mechanism of software configuration in Windows was originally a text file format that comprised text lines with one key–value pair per line, organized into sections.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] This format was used for operating system components, such as device drivers, fonts, and startup launchers.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] INI files were also generally used by applications to store individual settings.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] The format was maintained in 16-bit Microsoft Windows platforms up through Windows 3.1x.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Starting with Windows 95 Microsoft favored the use of the Windows Registry and began to steer developers away from using INI files for configuration.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] All subsequent versions of Windows have used the Windows Registry for system configuration, but applications built on the .NET Framework use special XML *.config* files.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] The initialization-file functions are still available in Windows and developers may still use them.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Besides Windows software, platform-agnostic software may use this file format for configuration.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Some Unix-like config files also use a similar format.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] INI is human-readable and simple to parse, so it is a usable format for configuration files that do not require much greater complexity.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] What follows is a non-exhaustive list of places in which INI files appear.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] The following example file has two sections: one for the owner of the software, and one for a payroll database connection.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Comments record the last person who modified the file and the reason for modification.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] In its broader sense, INI is an informal format which lends itself well to ad-hoc implementation while remaining human-configurable.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Consequently, many varying specifications (where sometimes a parser implementation is the only specification ever written) exist, called *INI dialects*.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] INI interpretations depend a lot on personal taste and the needs of the computing environment, such as whitespace preservation, field type information, case sensitivity, or preferred comment delimiters.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Nonetheless, *INI-flavoured* implementations typically share common design features: a text file consisting of a key–value pair on each line, delimited by an equals sign, organized into sections denoted by square brackets.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] In its most complicated interpretation, the INI format is able to express arbitrary S-expressions, making it equivalent to standardized formats like XML or JSON, albeit with a syntax which is not set in stone and to some may feel more comfortable.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] As the INI file format is not rigidly defined, many parsers support features beyond those that form the common core.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Attempts have been made to create parsers able to support as many dialects as possible.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Data in INI is held in key–value pairs called *key* or *property*.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] *Key* may thus either refer to the entire key–value pair or only its key.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] In its textual representation, the key–value pair is represented by either a line or a multiline where the start of the value is indicated by a delimiter, most often an equals sign (`=`, ASCII 0x3D) but sometimes also a colon (`:`, ASCII 0x3A) or whitespace (occasionally used in the GNU world).
[src:ini-format/ini-file] The key's key appears to the left of the delimiter, is often non-empty and should not contain the delimiter.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Some flavours allow escape sequences in the value.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] In the Windows implementation, the equals sign and the semicolon are reserved characters and cannot appear in the key.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Any whitespace surrounding the key is stripped by the parser.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] The value can contain any character (in Windows-style, no whitespace surrounds the delimiter: e.g.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Key–value pairs may be grouped under a *section*.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Some INI dialects require every key–value pair to be in a section, some allow so-called *global properties*.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] When key–value pairs are grouped, the section name appears on a line by itself, enclosed in square brackets (`[`, ASCII 0x5B, and `]`, ASCII 0x5D), and applies to all key–value pairs on subsequent lines until another section is declared.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] There is no explicit "end of section" delimiter (such as e.g.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Thus, sections syntactically cannot be arbitrarily nested.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] When required, nesting can be implemented through flattening one's hierarchy and concatenating with a custom delimiter character inside the section name (often `.`, ASCII 0x2E).
[src:ini-format/ini-file] One level of nesting is often supported, called *subsections*.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Some parsers did not offer nesting support at all and were hierarchy-blind, but nesting could still be partially emulated by exploiting the fact that `[A.B.C]` constitutes a unique identifier.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Section and property names in Windows are case insensitive.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Most Unix-style INI interpretations forbid case folding altogether, although case folding for the section name or key is sometimes allowed.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] A line with contiguous trailing whitespace followed by a semicolon (`;`, ASCII 0x3E) indicates a comment.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Some INI dialects furthermore allow use of the number sign (`#`, ASCII 0x23) to denote a comment, mirroring Unix shell comments.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Some INI dialects but not all allow a comment on a key–value pair line or section line (called *in-line comment*), where some require whitespace separating the value or section closing bracket from the comment.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] The number sign might be nonetheless included in the key name in some dialects and ignored as such.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Comment lines are designed to be ignored by a parser.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Under the WinAPI's *GetPrivateProfileString*'s dialect, comments must occur on lines by themselves.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] The order of properties in a section and the order of sections in a file is irrelevant.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Most implementations only support having one property with a given name in a section.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] The second occurrence of a property name may cause an abort, it may be ignored (and the value discarded), or it may override the first occurrence (with the first value discarded).
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Some programs use duplicate property names to implement multi-valued properties.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Interpretation of multiple section declarations with the same name also varies.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] In some implementations, duplicate sections simply merge their properties, as if they occurred contiguously.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Others may abort or ignore some aspect of the INI file.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Some implementations allow values to be quoted, typically using double quotes and/or apostrophes.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] This allows for explicit declaration of whitespace, and/or for quoting of special characters (equals, semicolon, etc.).
[src:ini-format/ini-file] The standard Windows function GetPrivateProfileString supports this, and will remove quotation marks that surround the values.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Emulating C syntax, some dialects allow line folding by a backslash (`\`, ASCII 0x5C) as the last character on a line.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] In such *line continuation*, backslashes followed immediately by EOL (end-of-line) cause the backslash and line break to be dropped, transforming the document's lines into *logical lines*.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Some dialects offer varying support for character escaping, typically with the backslash character (`\`, ASCII 0x5C) as a metacharacter and emulating C syntax.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] It is not wise to blindly interpret escape sequences as some specifications explicitly mute their metacharacter for common escape sequences.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Under Windows, the *Profile API* is the programming interface used to read and write settings from classic Windows `.ini` files.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] For example, the GetPrivateProfileString function retrieves a string from the specified section in an initialization file.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] The third parameter of the `GetPrivateProfileString` function is the default value, which are `"127.0.0.1"` and `143` respectively in the two function calls above.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] If the argument supplied for this parameter is `NULL`, the default is an empty string, `""`.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Under Unix, many different configuration libraries exist to access INI files.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] They are often already included in frameworks and toolkits.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Examples of INI parsers for Unix include GLib, iniparser and libconfini.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Initialization file mapping creates a mapping between an INI file and the Windows registry.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] It was introduced with Windows NT and Windows 95 as a way to migrate from storing settings in classic .ini files to the new registry.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] File mapping traps the Profile API calls and, using settings from the IniFileMapping Registry section, directs reads and writes to appropriate places in the Registry.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Using the example below, a string call could be made to fetch the *name* key from the *owner* section from a settings file called, say, dbsettings.ini.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] If this exists, it looks for an entry name matching the requested section.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] If an entry is found, INI mapping uses its value as a pointer to another part of the Registry.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] It then looks up the requested INI setting in that part of the Registry.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] If no matching entry name is found and there is an entry under the *(Default)* entry name, INI mapping uses that instead.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Thus each section name does not need its own entry.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] where the "*name*" Registry entry name is found to match the requested INI key.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] The value of "John Doe" is then returned to the Profile call.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] In this case, the @ prefix on the default prevents any reads from going to the dbsettings.ini file on disk.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] The result is that any settings not found in the Registry are not looked for in the INI file.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] The "*database*" Registry entry does not have the @ prefix on the value; thus, for the `[database]` section *only*, settings in the Registry are taken first followed by settings in the dbsettings.ini file on disk.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Starting with Windows 95, Microsoft began strongly promoting the use of the Windows Registry over INI files.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] INI files are typically limited to two levels (sections and properties) and do not handle binary data well.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] This decision, however, has not been immune to critiques, due to the fact that the registry is monolithic, opaque, and binary, must be in sync with the filesystem, and represents a single point of failure for the operating system.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Later, XML-based configuration files became a popular choice for encoding configuration in text files.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] XML allows arbitrarily complex levels and nesting and has standard mechanisms for encoding binary data.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] More recently, data serialization formats, such as JSON, TOML, and YAML, can serve as configuration formats.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] These three alternative formats can nest arbitrarily but have a syntax different from INI.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] Among them, TOML most closely resembles INI, but the idea to make TOML deliberately compatible with a large subset of INI was rejected.
[src:ini-format/ini-file] The newest INI parsers, however, also allow arbitrarily deep nesting like XML, JSON, TOML, and YAML, offer equivalent support of typed values and Unicode, although they keep the informal status of INI files by allowing multiple syntaxes for expressing the same thing.
[src:ini-format/property-list] In the macOS, iOS, NeXTSTEP, and GNUstep programming frameworks, **property list** files are files that store serialized objects.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Property list files use the filename extension `.plist`, and thus are often referred to as **p-list** files.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Property list files are often used to store a user's settings.
[src:ini-format/property-list] They are also used to store information about bundles and applications, a task served by the resource fork in the old Mac OS.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Property lists are also used for localization strings for development.
[src:ini-format/property-list] These files use the `.strings` or `.stringsdict` extensions.
[src:ini-format/property-list] The former is a "reduced" old-style plist containing only one dictionary without the braces (see propertyListFromStringsFileFormat), while the latter is a fully fledged plist.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Xcode also uses a `.pbxproj` extension for old-style plists used as project files.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Since the data represented by property lists is somewhat abstract, the underlying file format can be implemented in many ways.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Namely, NeXTSTEP used one format to represent a property list, and the subsequent GNUstep and macOS frameworks introduced differing formats.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Under NeXTSTEP, property lists were designed to be human-readable and edited by hand, serialized to ASCII in a syntax somewhat like a programming language.
[src:ini-format/property-list] One limitation of the original NeXT property list format is that it could not represent an NSValue (number, Boolean, etc.) object.
[src:ini-format/property-list] As a result, these values would have to be converted to string, and "fuzzily" recovered by the application.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Another limitation is that there is no official 8-bit encoding defined.
[src:ini-format/property-list] The defaults utility, introduced in OPENSTEP (1996), can be used to manipulate plist files used for storage of preferences (known as *defaults* in NeXTSTEP, hence the name) on the command line via their preferences domain, and this utility can be used to edit arbitrary plist files.
[src:ini-format/property-list] This utility superseded three older commands (dread, dwrite, and dremove).
[src:ini-format/property-list] GNUstep adopts the NeXTSTEP format, with additions for representing NSValue and NSDate data types.
[src:ini-format/property-list] The new typed entries have the form <**T*...>, where *T* is a one-letter type code.
[src:ini-format/property-list] For example, an NSValue of Boolean YES is represented as <*BY> and NSDate objects are represented as `<*DYYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS +ZZZZ>`.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Binary data can also use the more efficient base64 format as <[ b64... ]>.
[src:ini-format/property-list] The 8-bit problem is implicitly solved as well, as most deployments use UTF-8.
[src:ini-format/property-list] GNUstep also has its own binary format, NSPropertyListGNUstepBinaryFormat, implemented in NSSerialization.
[src:ini-format/property-list] This format is defined recursively like the textual formats, with a single-byte type marker preceding some data.
[src:ini-format/property-list] A form of string interning is supported via a GS-extension shouldBeCompact switch.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Two relative independent plist handlers are found in GNUstep: the CFPropertyList in libs-core-base (CoreFoundation), and the NSPropertyList in libs-base (Foundation Kit).
[src:ini-format/property-list] Both support the binary and XML forms used by macOS to some degree, but the latter is a lot more complete.
[src:ini-format/property-list] For example, the two GNUstep-specific formats are only handled in the latter.
[src:ini-format/property-list] GNUstep provides a set of plist command-line tools based on NSPropertyList, including a version of pl and defaults.
[src:ini-format/property-list] While macOS can also read the NeXTSTEP format, Apple sets it aside in favor of two new formats of its own, one XML-based and the other binary.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Apple also has a partially-compatible JSON format (NSJSONSerialization).
[src:ini-format/property-list] In Mac OS X 10.0, the NeXTSTEP format was deprecated, and a new XML format was introduced, with a public DTD defined by Apple.
[src:ini-format/property-list] The XML format supports non-ASCII characters and storing NSValue objects (which, unlike GNUstep's ASCII property list format, Apple's ASCII property list format does not support).
[src:ini-format/property-list] Since XML files, however, are not the most space-efficient means of storage, Mac OS X 10.2 introduced a new format where property list files are stored as binary files.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Starting with Mac OS X 10.4, this is the default format for preference files.
[src:ini-format/property-list] In Mac OS X 10.7, support for reading and writing files in JSON format was introduced.
[src:ini-format/property-list] JSON and property lists are not fully compatible with each other, though.
[src:ini-format/property-list] For example, property lists have native date and data types, which the JSON format does not support.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Conversely, JSON permits `null` values while property lists do not support explicit nulls.
[src:ini-format/property-list] The old defaults tool from NeXTSTEP remains available.
[src:ini-format/property-list] The /usr/libexec/PlistBuddy command provides an interactive plist editor.
[src:ini-format/property-list] The plutil utility (introduced in Mac OS X 10.2) can be used to check the syntax of property lists, or convert a property list file from one format to another.
[src:ini-format/property-list] It also supports converting plists to Objective-C or Swift object literals.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Like the Cocoa NSPropertyListSerialization it is built on, it takes "old-style" inputs, but does not convert to this type.
[src:ini-format/property-list] The pl utility is introduced in Mac OS X v10.5.
[src:ini-format/property-list] It takes any input and tries to generate "old-style" plists.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Like the GNUstep version, it appears to use the description property of Foundation types found in plists, which Apple has specified to produce valid old-style plists.
[src:ini-format/property-list] In terms of the internals, Apple provides an open source parser for old style, XML, and binary formats in their C Core Foundation code as CFPropertyList.
[src:ini-format/property-list] However, all the utilities and most parts of the system use the closed-source NSPropertyList parser from the Obj-C Foundation Kit.
[src:ini-format/property-list] The Swift reimplementation is open source, but is not guaranteed to be identical.
[src:ini-format/property-list] XML and JSON property lists are hand-editable in any text editor.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Additionally, Apple provides support in Xcode for editing property lists in a hierarchical viewer/editor that can handle plists formatted in binary or XML, but not JSON.
[src:ini-format/property-list] As of Mac OS X 10.4, Apple provides an AppleScript interface for reading property list files through the System Events application.
[src:ini-format/property-list] As of Mac OS X 10.5, Apple provides an AppleScript interface for editing, creating and writing property list files as well.
[src:ini-format/property-list] The binary file format is documented in a comment block in the Core Foundation C code source file (CF/CFBinaryPList.c) for Apple's open sourced implementation of binary plists in its Foundation library.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Apple describes the implementation as opaque in its plist(5) manual page documentation, which means that reliance on the format is discouraged.
[src:ini-format/property-list] In the binary file format the magic number (the first few bytes of the file which indicate that it's a valid plist file) is the text **bplist**, followed by two bytes indicating the version of the format.
[src:ini-format/property-list] The binary file can store some information that cannot be captured in the XML or JSON file formats.
[src:ini-format/property-list] The array, set and dictionary binary types are made up of **pointers** - the objref and keyref entries - that index into an object table in the file.
[src:ini-format/property-list] This means that binary plists can capture the fact that - for example - a separate array and dictionary serialized into a file both have the same data element stored in them.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Converting such a binary file will result in a copy of the data element being placed into the XML file.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Additionally the binary file has a UID type that is used to identify data items when serialized.
[src:ini-format/property-list] This means that the marker byte is only found in files with a format version no lower than the "1?" magic number.
[src:ini-format/property-list] The precise way to parse them is more nebulous than the way to parse legacy types, since the CFBinaryPlist implementation only handles version "0?".
[src:ini-format/property-list] In practice, these types are never encountered, since NSKeyedArchiver is already capable of capturing these information.
[src:ini-format/property-list] A table of offsets follow the object table, which is then followed by a trailer containing information on the size and location of the two tables.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Since property lists do not capture all the information and data types required to describe an arbitrary object, an extra layer of encoding and decoding is often done.
[src:ini-format/property-list] The OpenStep specification abstracts the operation of serializing any NSObject under the NSCoding protocol.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Any class implementing this protocol can have its instances serialized by a NSCoder subclass to some other format.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Among other things, using an archiver allows for new datatypes to be encoded without changing the plist format itself and it is the preferred way for Apple to encode things like NSSets and null values.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Parsing the formats do prove a bit harder, since one more layer must be followed even for some classes plists were supposed to support.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Like the binary format which also has an object table, it is possible to create circular references in NSKeyedArchiver.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Since there is not a UID data type in XML, the integers are stored in a dictionary under the key "CF$UID".
[src:ini-format/property-list] Apple publishes an open-source NSKeyedArchiver in Swift Corelibs Foundation; like the closed-source Apple Foundation, it restricts output formats to binary and XML only.
[src:ini-format/property-list] It also has some test cases showing the results of serialization.
[src:ini-format/property-list] GNUstep also has a compatible implementation, which does not limit output formats.
[src:ini-format/property-list] There is not a single, standardized path language for property lists like XPath does for XML, but informal conventions used by various programs exist.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Neither format is able to express a key with the separator character in it.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Although best known on Apple or Darwin systems, including iOS and macOS, plist files are also present on Windows computers when Apple software, such as iTunes or Safari are installed.
[src:ini-format/property-list] On Windows, the files are typically binary files, although some applications may generate PLIST files in the other formats.
[src:ini-format/property-list] On Windows the Apple plist files are stored in the user's home directory under %USERPROFILE%\AppData\Roaming\Apple Computer.
[src:ini-format/property-list] These plist files on Windows typically store preferences and other information, rather than using the Windows registry.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Options for editing PLIST files on Windows are not as extensive as on macOS.
[src:ini-format/property-list] If the file is in the XML or JSON format with care a text editor such as Notepad++ can be used.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Apple ships a plutil.exe within its "Apple Application Support" package (which is part of iTunes), and it is identical to its macOS counterpart.
[src:ini-format/property-list] Introduced in 2006 and first released with NetBSD#4.0 (2007) is a proplib library, which can be used for serialising data between the kernel and userland.
[src:ini-format/property-list] It implements part of the XML plist language.
[src:ini-format/property-list] One of the sample users of proplib is the second revision of the sysmon envsys framework for system monitoring.
[src:ini-format/property-list] NetBSD's proplib library has also been ported to DragonFly in 2010, and is available since DragonFly BSD#2.8.
[src:ini-format/toml] Among other constructs, TOML's syntax primarily consists of key-value pairs, section names in square brackets, and comments delimited by a leading `#`.
[src:ini-format/toml] TOML's syntax is a superset of the INI format.
[src:ini-format/toml] Contrary to the INI format, which comprises multiple competing variants as a result of ad-hoc parsers, TOML has a formally agreed-upon syntax.
[src:ini-format/toml] TOML supports the following data types: string, integer, float, boolean, datetime, array, and table.
